<div id="review_2505481288" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2505481288" />
    <a title="Betsy Robinson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5149179-betsy-robinson"><img alt="Betsy Robinson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1404493492p2/5149179.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2505481288?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Betsy Robinson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Betsy Robinson" href="/user/show/5149179-betsy-robinson">Betsy Robinson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2505481288" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11560748437397756467">Completely without context, here are two quotes which I believe express Maggie O’Farrell’s <i>raison d’etre</i> for this astoundingly haunting book:<br/><blockquote>We are all, Esme decides, just vessels though which identities pass: we are lent features, gestures, habits, then we hand them on. Nothing is our own. We begin in the world as anagrams of our antecedents. (118)</blockquote><br/>And then the next paragraph ends with:<br/><blockquote>She would like to feel the ceaseless drag of the currents flexing beneath her. But she fears it may frighten th</blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText11560748437397756467" style="display:none">Completely without context, here are two quotes which I believe express Maggie O’Farrell’s <i>raison d’etre</i> for this astoundingly haunting book:<br /><blockquote>We are all, Esme decides, just vessels though which identities pass: we are lent features, gestures, habits, then we hand them on. Nothing is our own. We begin in the world as anagrams of our antecedents. (118)</blockquote><br />And then the next paragraph ends with:<br /><blockquote>She would like to feel the ceaseless drag of the currents flexing beneath her. But she fears it may frighten the girl. Esme is frightening—this much she has learnt.</blockquote><br />Esme Lennox, institutionalized for sixty years and finally rescued by her similarly free-spirited great niece (the girl referred to in the last quote), is a character I might have been in another life, and I find it a little distressing that the cover copy calls this a “gothic” story. The only thing about it that resonates with that word is horror. But there is nothing supernatural about that horror. To the contrary: it is an authentically horrifying story about a real woman who embodies what Joseph Campbell described as our reason for being alive: “People say that what we’re all seeking is a meaning for life. . . I think that what we’re seeking is an experience of being alive, so that our life experiences on the purely physical plane will have resonances with our innermost being and reality, so that we actually feel the rapture of being alive.” Esme is a normal person who is judged dangerous for not being repressed, emotionally deadened, and in denial. And labeling that as “gothic,” gives it a weirdness that mischaracterizes the book and, in some way, reflects the very bias of those who judged Esme. <br /><br />So, in short, I loved this brilliant, original, exciting, horrifying book and I disliked the cover copy. <i>The Vanishing Act of Esme Lennox</i> is so much bigger and more profound than a weird work of genre fiction.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11560748437397756467" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


