    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1199481472" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1199481472" />
    <a title="Connie G" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5364077-connie-g"><img alt="Connie G" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1307502493p2/5364077.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1199481472?book_show_action=true">Jul 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Connie G" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Connie G" href="/user/show/5364077-connie-g">Connie G</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=scotland">scotland</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=mental-health">mental-health</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1199481472" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7898901994867878129">Iris receives a phone call that her great-aunt Esme--who she never knew existed--was going to be released from Scotland&apos;s Cauldstone Hospital. (In the 1990s, many British patients were released from the confinement of mental hospitals. They had been institutionalized because their behavior did not fit in with polite society&apos;s norms, rather than because they were truly mentally ill.) Iris takes Esme home for the weekend to the older family home that Esme had lived in during her teen years.<br/><br/>The sto</span>
  <span id="freeText7898901994867878129" style="display:none">Iris receives a phone call that her great-aunt Esme--who she never knew existed--was going to be released from Scotland's Cauldstone Hospital. (In the 1990s, many British patients were released from the confinement of mental hospitals. They had been institutionalized because their behavior did not fit in with polite society's norms, rather than because they were truly mentally ill.) Iris takes Esme home for the weekend to the older family home that Esme had lived in during her teen years.<br /><br />The story is told through three voices--Iris, Esme, and Esme's older sister Kitty whose troubling, vague confessions break through the confusion of dementia. Esme and Kitty spent their early years in colonial India where Esme is subjected to the cruel treatment of a mother who dislikes her. The story then moves to Edinburgh where the headstrong, precocious Esme has no interest in social events designed to snag a husband. After Esme is upset following a traumatic event, her family confines her in a mental institution in Fife.<br /><br />In addition to Esme and Kitty the story has another interesting sibling relationship--Iris and her stepbrother Alex. Iris is also an unconventional, free-spirited young woman who does not always follow the dictates of society. One wonders if she would have met with Esme's fate if she was living in a different time.<br /><br />It's terrifying to think that odd, nonconformist women were confined for life in mental institutions on such flimsy evidence in Victorian times. I'll be remembering this book for a while for its atmospheric writing and its shocking ending.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7898901994867878129" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


