          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3593918586" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5481664098348779422">Update: January 5, 2021 <br/>I stand by my 5-star review from October, 2020. This time around I noticed more and liked it perhaps even more than the first time around. If nothing else, I wasn&apos;t confused this time by all the abrupt changes of narrator.<br/><br/>Wow, just wow! This is a very hard-to-explain novel about two sisters, Esme and Kitty Lennox, who we meet in India where they live with their Brit family with whom they move as teens to Scotland to live with a grandmother. Then zoom! we are hurled into t</span>
  <span id="freeText5481664098348779422" style="display:none">Update: January 5, 2021 <br />I stand by my 5-star review from October, 2020. This time around I noticed more and liked it perhaps even more than the first time around. If nothing else, I wasn't confused this time by all the abrupt changes of narrator.<br /><br />Wow, just wow! This is a very hard-to-explain novel about two sisters, Esme and Kitty Lennox, who we meet in India where they live with their Brit family with whom they move as teens to Scotland to live with a grandmother. Then zoom! we are hurled into the future to what seems like the 1990's when Iris Lockhart is told of a great aunt she never knew existed as she is released from an asylum that is closing. The powers that be in that asylum of course want Iris, the only relative they know of, to take care of her (Esme). And then zoom! we're back in India, then zoom! back in Scotland, back and forth in time and space that for some reason I did not have trouble tracking with*. A swirling, emotional and ultimately very satisfying novel. As friend Debbie, said at the close of her dynamite review: (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1629619763?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a>)<br /><br /><i>"Beauteous language. Complex, juicy plot. Intriguing characters. Surprises."</i><br /><br />*well, not quite true! I listened to this book, wonderfully read by Anne Flosnik, but hard to track with until I realized that three main characters were telling their story in this swirling novel . . . with no announcement that point of view was about to change, often abruptly. Once I clicked into this, I became totally immersed, had a hard time putting this down and didn't want it to end! <br /><br /><i>Why I'm rereading this:</i> Jan 1, 2021: I nominated this for the January read in the Mystery, Crime and Thriller group and it was one of two winners. Since I'll be moderating the discussion, I wanted to have it fresh in my mind. Interesting that the book begins on New Year's Eve, given that was just yesterday. <br /><br /><i>Why I'm reading this:</i> Buddy read with friend, Diane. Neither of us has read O'Farrell, both of us are intrigued, and this is where we are starting our exploration of her work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5481664098348779422" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


